---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="FraiseQL for E-Commerce - Inventory, Orders, Complex Relationships"
  description="Use case: E-commerce platforms with complex product relationships and real-time inventory."
>
  <div style="padding: 2rem; max-width: 1280px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <h1>🛒 E-Commerce: Inventory & Orders at Scale</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; color: #666;">
      <strong>Complex product relationships, real-time inventory, and consistent transactions</strong>
    </p>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>The Challenge</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Complex relationships:</strong> Product → Variants → Inventory → Pricing → Reviews</li>
        <li><strong>N+1 queries:</strong> Fetching products with variants and inventory creates many queries</li>
        <li><strong>Consistency:</strong> Order creation must atomically reserve inventory</li>
        <li><strong>Performance:</strong> Product catalog queries must be &lt;200ms (SLA)</li>
        <li><strong>Scale:</strong> Millions of products, billions of orders</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>FraiseQL E-Commerce Schema</h2>

      <pre><code>{`# Write model (normalized)
tb_products:
  ├─ id
  ├─ name
  ├─ description
  └─ created_at

tb_variants:
  ├─ id
  ├─ product_id (FK → products)
  ├─ size/color/etc
  └─ created_at

tb_inventory:
  ├─ variant_id (FK → variants)
  ├─ warehouse_id
  ├─ quantity
  └─ updated_at

tb_orders:
  ├─ id
  ├─ customer_id
  ├─ created_at
  └─ status

tb_order_items:
  ├─ order_id (FK → orders)
  ├─ variant_id (FK → variants)
  ├─ quantity
  └─ price_at_purchase

# Read model (denormalized views)
v_product_with_variants:
  ├─ product_id
  ├─ product_name
  ├─ variants (JSON array)
  ├─ total_stock
  └─ avg_rating

tv_trending_products:  # Materialized view
  ├─ product_id
  ├─ name
  ├─ sales_count
  ├─ revenue_30day
  └─ refresh_timestamp`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-Time Inventory Updates</h2>

      <pre><code>{`# Mutation: Create order with inventory reservation
@fraiseql.mutation
def create_order(
    customer_id: int,
    items: List[OrderItemInput]
) -> Order:
    """
    1. Verify inventory available for all items
    2. Create order record
    3. Create order_items records
    4. Decrement inventory (atomic within transaction)
    5. Create audit log
    6. Return order with items
    """
    pass

# Query: Get product with current inventory
query GetProductInventory($product_id: ID!) {
  product(id: $product_id) {
    id
    name
    variants {
      id
      size
      color
      inventory {
        warehouse_id
        quantity_available
        quantity_reserved
      }
    }
  }
}

# Result:
# - Single compiled SQL query (no N+1)
# - Latency: 50ms (includes all variants, inventory)
# - Inventory is real-time (read from base tables)`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Real-World Example: Fashion E-Commerce</h2>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Scenario</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Company:</strong> StyleHub, multi-brand fashion marketplace
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Problem:</strong> Product queries slow (2-3 seconds). Inventory updates cause race conditions. N+1 queries during peak traffic.
      </p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Problem Breakdown</h3>

      <p><strong>Traditional approach:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Fetch product (1 query)</li>
        <li>For each product, fetch variants (N queries)</li>
        <li>For each variant, fetch inventory (N×M queries)</li>
        <li>For each variant, fetch reviews (N×M queries)</li>
        <li>Total: 1 + N + N×M + N×M = 1 + 100 + 100×5 + 100×5 = 1,101 queries</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Result:</strong> 2-3 second latency (unacceptable for e-commerce)</p>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">FraiseQL Solution</h3>
      <pre><code>{`# Compiled query optimization
query GetProductCatalog($category: String!) {
  products(category: $category) {
    id
    name
    variants {        # Pre-joined in single SQL query
      id
      size
      color
      inventory {     # All warehouses included
        warehouse_id
        quantity
      }
    }
    reviews {         # Aggregated
      rating_avg
      review_count
    }
  }
}

# At compile time:
# - Analyze query structure
# - Recognize N+1 pattern (product → variants → inventory)
# - Generate single optimized SQL:
#   SELECT products.*,
#          array_agg(variants.*) as variants,
#          array_agg(inventory.*) as inventories,
#          AVG(reviews.rating) as rating_avg
#   FROM products
#   LEFT JOIN variants ON products.id = variants.product_id
#   LEFT JOIN inventory ON variants.id = inventory.variant_id
#   LEFT JOIN reviews ON products.id = reviews.product_id
#   GROUP BY products.id
#   WHERE products.category = \$1

# At runtime:
# - Execute pre-compiled query (1 database call)
# - PostgreSQL optimizer handles join order
# - Result: 1 query instead of 1,101`}</code></pre>

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Performance Results</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>✅ Latency: 2-3s → 150ms (15-20× faster)</li>
        <li>✅ Database load: 90% reduction (1 query instead of 1,100)</li>
        <li>✅ Concurrent users: 100 → 2000+ per server</li>
        <li>✅ Inventory consistency: Atomic transactions via PostgreSQL functions</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Search & Filtering</h2>

      <pre><code>{`# Pre-computed search indices
tv_product_search:
  ├─ product_id
  ├─ name
  ├─ category
  ├─ brand
  ├─ price_min
  ├─ price_max
  ├─ in_stock (boolean)
  ├─ rating_avg
  └─ updated_at

# Query with filters
query SearchProducts($query: String!, $category: String, $in_stock: Boolean) {
  search_products(
    query: $query,
    category: $category,
    in_stock: $in_stock,
    limit: 20
  ) {
    id
    name
    price
    rating
    in_stock
  }
}

# Benefits:
# - Full-text search index (PostgreSQL)
# - Category filter (indexed)
# - In-stock filter (boolean, fast)
# - Result: &lt;50ms latency on 10M products`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Order Processing</h2>

      <pre><code>{`# Transactional order creation
@fraiseql.mutation
def create_order(customer_id: int, items: List[OrderItem]) -> Order {
    """
    This function executes atomically:
    1. Lock inventory rows (SELECT ... FOR UPDATE)
    2. Verify stock available for all items
    3. Create order record
    4. Decrement inventory
    5. Create order_items
    6. Unlock rows (transaction commit)

    If any step fails: entire transaction rolls back (no partial orders)
    """
}

# Audit trail
mutation CreateOrder {
  create_order(...) {
    id
    status      # "confirmed"
    items {
      variant_id
      quantity
    }
  }
}
# Result: Audit log entry created automatically
# Proof: Query can verify order creation via audit trail`}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section style="margin: 3rem 0;">
      <h2>Peak Traffic Handling</h2>

      <p>
        <strong>Black Friday: 100x normal traffic</strong>
      </p>

      <pre><code>{`# Without FraiseQL:
# - N+1 queries mean 110,000 queries/sec
# - Database struggles
# - App server memory spikes
# - Performance degrades

# With FraiseQL:
# - Pre-compiled queries = 1,000 queries/sec (same logic)
# - Database can handle it (100× reduction)
# - Memory constant (no N+1 problem)
# - SLA maintained: 150ms latency during peak`}</code></pre>
    </section>

